<article title='Demographics_of_the_Central_African_Republic'><paragraph>This article is about the<space/><link><target>demographics</target><part>demographic</part></link><space/>features of the<space/><link><target>population</target></link><space/>of the<space/><link><target>Central African Republic</target></link>, including<space/><link><target>population density</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Ethnic group</target><part>ethnicity</part></link>, education level, health of the populace, economic status, religious affiliations and other aspects of the population.</paragraph><paragraph><link><target>Image:Central African Republic-demography.png</target><part>thumb</part><part>300px</part><part>right</part><part>Demographics of Central African Republic, Data of<space/><link><target>FAO</target></link>, year 2005 ; Number of inhabitants in thousands.</part></link>There are more than 80 ethnic groups in the<space/><link><target>Central African Republic</target></link><space/>(CAR), each with its own language. About 50% are<space/><link><target>Gbaya people</target><part>Baya-Mandjia</part></link>, 40%<space/><link><target>Banda (CAR)</target><part>Banda</part></link><space/>(largely located in the northern and central parts of the country), and 7% are<space/><link><target>M'Baka</target></link><space/>(southwestern corner of the CAR).<space/><link><target>Sangho</target></link>, the language of a small group along the<space/><link><target>Oubangui</target></link><space/>River, is the national language spoken by the majority of Central Africans. Only a small part of the population has more than an elemental knowledge of French, the official language.</paragraph><paragraph>More than 55% of the population of the CAR lives in rural areas. The chief agricultural areas are around the<space/><link><target>Bossangoa</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Bambari</target></link>.<space/><link><target>Bangui</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Berberati</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Bangassou</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Bossangoa</target></link><space/>are the most densely populated urban centers.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Population</heading><paragraph>According to the 2010 revision of the World Population Prospects the total population was 4 401 000 in 2010, compared to only 1 327 000 in 1950. The proportion of children below the age of 15 in 2010 was 40.4%, 55.6% was between 15 and 65 years of age, while 4% was 65 years or older.<extension extension_name='ref' name="WPP 2010"><link type='external' href='http://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/index.htm'>Population Division of the Department of Economic and Social Affairs of the United Nations Secretariat, World Population Prospects: The 2010 Revision</link></extension></paragraph><table class="wikitable" style="text-align: right;"><tablerow><tablehead></tablehead><tablehead width="80pt">Total population (x 1000)</tablehead><tablehead width="80pt">Population aged 014 (%)</tablehead><tablehead width="80pt">Population aged 1564 (%)</tablehead><tablehead width="80pt">Population aged 65+ (%)</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>1950</tablecell><tablecell>1 327</tablecell><tablecell>36.2</tablecell><tablecell>58.7</tablecell><tablecell>5.1</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>1955</tablecell><tablecell>1 399</tablecell><tablecell>37.0</tablecell><tablecell>58.3</tablecell><tablecell>4.7</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>1960</tablecell><tablecell>1 504</tablecell><tablecell>38.2</tablecell><tablecell>57.5</tablecell><tablecell>4.3</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>1965</tablecell><tablecell>1 649</tablecell><tablecell>39.6</tablecell><tablecell>56.2</tablecell><tablecell>4.2</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>1970</tablecell><tablecell>1 829</tablecell><tablecell>40.6</tablecell><tablecell>55.3</tablecell><tablecell>4.1</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell>1975</tablecell><tablecell>2 017</tablecell><tablecell>41.7</t